Watch some videos, read some books, play around with the program every chance you get. If you‚Äôve been using GarageBand for some time you‚Äôll be able to pick it up pretty well. It‚Äôs similar basics with a lot more control. The IU for GB is pretty sweet, but that‚Äôs because of its limitations so that will take some getting used to. Don‚Äôt go all in, look for shit in the program you‚Äôre already familiar with and go from there. If you want to take production seriously, it‚Äôs worth the jump!

I‚Äôm not sure about logic, but with ableton live (which I hear are pretty similar for the most part) it‚Äôs far more complex and in depth. Pretty much anything can be automated, which in itself is a huge advantage. There aren‚Äôt weird bugs that cause the program to crash because you pressed the wrong icon and the wrong time. You have far more control over everything. It‚Äôs a huge difference. 

All that being said, I use GarageBand because I‚Äôm broke af and fell in love with it because of its simplicity (it‚Äôs also where I started). As much as I do miss using Ableton, it‚Äôs kind of nice having something a little more basic as this all has levelled back into being just a hobby for me. If you want to take this seriously and don‚Äôt want to just be able to make music, but learn more about how everything works and understand the mechanics behind it (which will give you a huge leap forward), leave GarageBand behind. If you just want to have a shitload of fun making music, GarageBand is definitely where it‚Äôs at.
